00:18:17.099 --> 00:18:23.300
about this one here in a little bit. And then also multitasking, like training your chef to

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:29.339
prepare two, maybe three meals at the exact same time. So we're going to go through each

00:18:29.339 --> 00:18:33.380
one of those steps, we're going to talk about it in the context of our Shiny restaurant, and

00:18:33.380 --> 00:18:37.780
then how that translates over to our Shiny application. And we're going to start with

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:43.939
preparing ingredients in advance. So again, let's say your chef, they get an order for a ham

00:18:43.939 --> 00:18:49.420
and cheese sandwich. And when that order comes in, if this is their starting material, this

00:18:49.420 --> 00:18:53.780
raw material, they're gonna have to spend some time cutting tomatoes, slicing the bread, slicing

00:18:53.780 --> 00:18:59.140
the ham, and that's going to take time. And what would be much faster is if this was their

00:18:59.140 --> 00:19:03.699
starting material, all the ingredients were prepared in advance, they can simply grab each

00:19:03.699 --> 00:19:07.500
component, assemble the sandwich super quick, and then deliver it to the end user or the

00:19:07.500 --> 00:19:15.380
customer. So for Shiny apps, this essentially means preparing your data in advance. And 99% of

00:19:15.380 --> 00:19:22.140
all times when you have slow Shiny applications is likely because the data is too large. And

00:19:22.180 --> 00:19:26.420
you know, sometimes that's going to be kind of unavoidable. But other times we can prepare

00:19:26.420 --> 00:19:31.020
that data in advance, so that only the data that's needed for that Shiny application is

00:19:31.020 --> 00:19:37.380
processed. So a few different things to consider. Make sure when you're reading a data to your

00:19:37.380 --> 00:19:43.099
Shiny application that you read and process that data only once. You want to try to not get into a

00:19:43.099 --> 00:19:48.420
situation where every single time someone slides a bar in your Shiny application, it re-reads in

00:19:48.420 --> 00:19:54.020
the data, and then re-reads in the data over and over and over again. You should also think

00:19:54.020 --> 00:19:59.739
about, especially large data sets, having that stored somewhere else and not within your Shiny

00:19:59.739 --> 00:20:06.619
application itself. So maybe have it stored in a database. Or maybe move any data processing

00:20:06.619 --> 00:20:12.180
steps. So if you have to like transform your data or even model your data, you can actually try to

00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:16.579
move this outside of your Shiny app. You can have it within a pin. And so if you've never heard of

00:20:16.579 --> 00:20:22.699
pins before, it's a way to take data and store it either at like a S3 bucket, Bitbucket,

00:20:23.819 --> 00:20:29.540
PositConnect can also store pins. Or you can take some of that data processing and you can put it

00:20:29.540 --> 00:20:34.500
into an R Markdown document and schedule that to run on PositConnect. Or you can serve it as a

00:20:34.500 --> 00:20:41.660
Plumber API. These are all great options. Really the take home here, Shiny is a visualization tool.

00:20:41.780 --> 00:20:48.260
It was never quite designed to be a huge compute workhorse. And so anytime you can take these

00:20:48.260 --> 00:20:53.500
data transformation steps and move it outside of the Shiny application, the better.

00:20:54.500 --> 00:20:59.020
All right, so going back to our Shiny restaurant, another way that we can improve operations is to

00:20:59.020 --> 00:21:04.939
keep our kitchen organized and updated. So I've had to ask everyone here on the line, which kitchen

00:21:04.939 --> 00:21:09.260
would you prefer to work in? Would you rather one on the left where everything's nice and organized?

00:21:09.579 --> 00:21:13.420
Or do you prefer the one on the right where it's just a little bit more cluttered and disheveled,

00:21:13.420 --> 00:21:17.660
and you may not know where everything is? Now I'm going to guess you'll probably say one on the left.

00:21:17.819 --> 00:21:23.739
And let's say our chef, they said, hey, I need a new knife, a new kitchen knife to prepare the meal.

00:21:23.739 --> 00:21:30.140
As a manager, it would be a very poor decision to provide them with a very rusty, old, dull knife,

00:21:30.140 --> 00:21:34.219
or even worse, provide them with a medieval sword, which is not the right tool for the job.

00:21:34.219 --> 00:21:40.780
And essentially, we want to provide them with a very sharp, clean kitchen knife so they can do their job correctly.

00:21:40.780 --> 00:21:46.780
So when it comes to our Shiny application, this means optimizing and organizing your code and functions.

00:21:46.780 --> 00:21:49.979
And there's a lot of different ways you can do that, and I'm just going to talk about a few.

00:21:51.500 --> 00:21:55.099
You always want to make sure that you're using the fastest functions,

00:21:55.099 --> 00:21:59.339
and you may be asking yourself, like, how do I figure that out? Like, well, Profiz is one way.

00:21:59.979 --> 00:22:03.099
You can kind of take a bunch of functions and compare them to the other,

00:22:03.099 --> 00:22:07.099
but just some other tools, including the very fantastic Bench package,

00:22:07.099 --> 00:22:11.660
which has a mark function, so you can benchmark various functions. We'll see that here in a second.

00:22:12.859 --> 00:22:17.260
You also want to make sure you call code in the correct spot, and I've alluded to this briefly

00:22:17.260 --> 00:22:22.459
about making sure that data is not being re-read in every single time someone interacts with your Shiny app.

00:22:23.819 --> 00:22:28.380
Avoid copying your code. So this is just a way to keep your Shiny applications organized,

00:22:28.380 --> 00:22:30.939
so putting code into functions, for example.

00:22:30.939 --> 00:22:35.500
And R is great for vectorized operations, so any time you can vectorize anything,

00:22:35.500 --> 00:22:40.540
that's certainly going to be the way to go. And then, if you haven't heard of Shiny modules,

00:22:40.540 --> 00:22:44.859
it's a great way to just organize your Shiny applications to separate modules,

00:22:44.859 --> 00:22:50.859
which can make troubleshooting and, again, just kind of consuming your applications significantly easier.

00:22:51.660 --> 00:22:55.900
So let's talk about a few of these steps, and we'll start right here with using your fastest functions.

00:22:56.859 --> 00:23:02.060
So in this slide, at the very top, we're seeing two functions, all right? Function, this first one,

00:23:02.060 --> 00:23:06.780
is simply just wrapping up the mean function. So we're finding the mean of a vector x,

00:23:06.780 --> 00:23:11.979
and we're going to call this function mean1. In the second function, we're going to call mean2,

00:23:11.979 --> 00:23:17.579
does the exact same thing, but we spell out mean, so we take the sum of x divided by the length of x.

00:23:17.579 --> 00:23:23.180
These will do the exact same thing, just two sliders apart. So we're going to call this function mean1.

00:23:23.579 --> 00:23:26.540
These will do the exact same thing, just two slightly different ways.

00:23:28.140 --> 00:23:32.859
And then down here, we're going to run the bench, the mark function, so benchmark,

00:23:32.859 --> 00:23:37.260
and we're basically going to compete mean1 versus mean2 and see which one's faster.

00:23:37.979 --> 00:23:42.619
You can get a lot of different output from this bench package and the mark function,

00:23:42.619 --> 00:23:48.459
including how the kind of the average minimum time, median time, and iterations per second.

00:23:48.540 --> 00:23:54.300
And it's pretty surprising, you can see that mean2 actually outperforms just the mean function.

00:23:54.939 --> 00:23:58.939
Now, I'm certainly not saying to go back into all your code and swap out mean for

00:23:58.939 --> 00:24:03.660
sum divided by length, because mean is a little bit easier to read, it's a little bit more concise.

00:24:04.300 --> 00:24:07.660
And, you know, just a couple of hundred microseconds, maybe that doesn't make that

00:24:07.660 --> 00:24:11.739
much of a difference. But, you know, there's certainly ways where you could think about,

00:24:11.739 --> 00:24:15.420
you know, maybe taking one function and competing it against another to see which

00:24:15.420 --> 00:24:19.660
one might be faster, especially if you use it multiple times in your Shiny application.

00:24:22.380 --> 00:24:26.619
Now, you also want to make sure you're calling code in the correct spot. So let me go through

00:24:26.619 --> 00:24:31.500
a quick example of where this might kind of show us heading into your Shiny applications.

00:24:32.060 --> 00:24:36.939
Here we have a function I'm going to create called myDataPrep. And it's just a made up

00:24:36.939 --> 00:24:41.180
function where the first thing it does is it reads in a CSV file, so some data,

00:24:41.739 --> 00:24:45.739
and then it takes that data, it filters it for some non important variables,

00:24:45.739 --> 00:24:48.859
it groups it by some other variables, and does some other slow functions.

00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:55.339
Now, what you don't want to do, and what I've alluded to before is have this function like

00:24:55.339 --> 00:24:59.819
this that reads in data somewhere in like a reactive function in your Shiny app,

00:24:59.819 --> 00:25:04.859
because essentially, anytime someone interacts with your app, and it calls this reactive function,

00:25:04.859 --> 00:25:09.500
it's going to reread in that data over and over and over again, which is just not necessary.

00:25:10.380 --> 00:25:15.260
So what we really want to do is take this myDataPrep function and move it outside of

00:25:15.260 --> 00:25:21.660
those reactive steps outside of your server, so that essentially, it's called once and only once.

00:25:24.540 --> 00:25:28.859
And then we have Shiny modules. Now, Shiny modules, some of you may use them today.

00:25:29.420 --> 00:25:33.660
But if you have any applications that are really starting to grow in complexity,

00:25:33.660 --> 00:25:38.300
it's becoming harder to manage to keep track of, you should really think about

00:25:38.939 --> 00:25:42.540
organizing your Shiny application and what's known as Shiny modules.

00:25:42.540 --> 00:25:46.619
So I'm not going to go into full depth of how to actually create Shiny modules,

00:25:46.619 --> 00:25:49.180
we have some great documentation on our Shiny website.

00:25:49.739 --> 00:25:54.140
But just to explain kind of conceptually what they are, let's say on the left hand side,

00:25:54.140 --> 00:25:58.140
this is your Shiny application, and each of these box corresponds to a different step.

00:25:58.780 --> 00:26:01.739
And you can see here just reading through it's a bunch of different steps,

00:26:01.739 --> 00:26:07.260
not an overly complex Shiny application. But you can see very quickly that certain

00:26:07.260 --> 00:26:11.819
steps are having impacts and interacting with other steps, arrows are starting to cross over

00:26:11.819 --> 00:26:16.619
each other, and it's starting to get a little bit complex, which then becomes harder to troubleshoot.

00:26:17.260 --> 00:26:24.140
And so what you can do is you can essentially break up the Shiny application into separate modules.

00:26:24.140 --> 00:26:29.260
So here we have a session module, an HPC module, data module, and a results module.

00:26:29.260 --> 00:26:34.459
And these are independent modules, and you can troubleshoot just a single module.

00:26:35.180 --> 00:26:38.859
And what's also really nice is you can take, for example, this data module,

00:26:38.859 --> 00:26:41.579
and you can incorporate it into a separate application.

00:26:41.579 --> 00:26:43.979
So they're portable between applications as well.

00:26:46.619 --> 00:26:50.859
All right, let's go back to our restaurant and talk about another way that we can hopefully

00:26:50.859 --> 00:26:55.660
improve performance. And that is to prepare the most popular meals in advance.

00:26:56.219 --> 00:27:01.260
So I think the best way to think about this, let's say your Shiny restaurant is actually a pizzeria.

00:27:01.900 --> 00:27:06.060
And let's say if 10 people walk into your restaurant,

00:27:06.060 --> 00:27:09.739
nine of them are going to order your world-famous margarita pizza.

00:27:10.540 --> 00:27:15.420
So because of that, you start to think, well, okay, maybe I can start preparing a bunch of

00:27:15.420 --> 00:27:21.180
margarita pizzas in advance when I first open up my doors. And that way, when people enter the

00:27:21.180 --> 00:27:26.219
front door, I can just quickly deliver that already prepared margarita pizza.

00:27:26.219 --> 00:27:29.339
So essentially, you can have all these margarita pizzas in this hotbox,

00:27:29.339 --> 00:27:35.819
ready to be delivered instantaneously. So for Shiny applications, this essentially means

00:27:35.819 --> 00:27:41.020
caching your outputs. And some of you may be familiar with this, but what is caching your

00:27:41.020 --> 00:27:47.099
outputs? What Shiny will do is it'll store that combination of your input and outputs,

00:27:47.099 --> 00:27:51.900
so kind of the output of these render and reactive functions. And if the application,

00:27:51.900 --> 00:27:57.900
if it sees that input, it'll generate the resulting output only once, and then it will

00:27:57.979 --> 00:28:06.140
store that output in a cache. And if those inputs are seen again, it can simply retrieve that value

00:28:06.140 --> 00:28:10.060
or that plot from the cache instead of having to recompute it over again.

00:28:11.099 --> 00:28:17.180
Let me show you kind of conceptually how this works. So here we have a render plot function.

00:28:17.180 --> 00:28:21.660
So I'm generating a plot here of the state of Maryland, which is where I live here in the

00:28:21.660 --> 00:28:27.500
United States. And to generate this plot, it just takes a single input right up here, where I input

00:28:27.500 --> 00:28:34.459
the state Maryland. So let's say this takes about four seconds to compute. Not super slow, but you

00:28:34.459 --> 00:28:39.819
know, still four seconds, the user is going to have to wait. So what I can do instead is I can

00:28:39.819 --> 00:28:44.939
take this render plot function and I can pipe it into the bind cache function. It's going to take

00:28:44.939 --> 00:28:51.260
that single state input. That way, when I go to indirect to this application, I select Maryland,

00:28:51.260 --> 00:28:56.859
it generates this plot once, which takes four seconds, and then it caches that plot. And then

00:28:56.859 --> 00:29:02.939
if another user or my future self comes back to this application and selects Maryland, rather than

00:29:02.939 --> 00:29:08.140
having to regenerate the plot, it can just grab the plot from the cache and deliver it in a fraction

00:29:08.140 --> 00:29:15.339
of the time. All right, and now we have multitasking, which is going to be our last step we'll talk

00:29:15.339 --> 00:29:20.699
about. So it'd be really nice if your chef at the exact same time could have a turkey going in the

00:29:20.699 --> 00:29:27.260
oven, maybe some pasta sauce on top of the and on the range here, right next to some stir fry,

00:29:27.260 --> 00:29:32.459
all going at the same time preparing three different meals simultaneously. So what does

00:29:32.459 --> 00:29:38.459
that mean for Shiny apps? Well, it means using something called asynchronous programming, which

00:29:38.459 --> 00:29:43.819
sounds pretty complex. But the reason why we have to do this async programming is because R is

00:29:43.819 --> 00:29:50.060
inherently a single threaded programming language, meaning that it's kind of hard to do two operations

00:29:50.060 --> 00:29:56.699
at the exact same time. So to implement this async programming, we have to use the help of

00:29:56.699 --> 00:30:03.020
some packages, specifically promises and the futures package. There's also another way you

00:30:03.020 --> 00:30:08.540
can do this by essentially offloading any of these steps to something like an API, which can be running

00:30:08.540 --> 00:30:13.739
on a separate R session outside of your Shiny application. This is optional, but it's always

00:30:13.739 --> 00:30:19.339
good practice again to move any of those data processing or compute steps outside of your Shiny

00:30:19.339 --> 00:30:26.939
app. All right, so let's talk about how to actually leverage async programming specifically

00:30:26.939 --> 00:30:32.140
as promises package. And we're just going to use this example Shiny application I have here,

00:30:32.140 --> 00:30:38.380
which I'm going to call analyze data app. This application does two things, it takes in some

00:30:38.380 --> 00:30:42.859
inputs, and you can either plot the data, which goes very fast, it only takes about a second to

00:30:42.859 --> 00:30:48.140
plot that data. Or you can run a model on that data, which takes a little bit more time to run

00:30:48.140 --> 00:30:53.739
about 60 seconds. And again, let's say this app is using a single R session or an R process.

00:30:55.660 --> 00:31:00.219
Some of these users, they log in, we have four users here, and the only thing they want to do

00:31:00.219 --> 00:31:05.020
is plot some data. And they're happy because this step is very fast, they click plot data,

00:31:05.020 --> 00:31:13.500
and within a second, that plot is returned to them. Similarly, maybe you have, maybe you have a

00:31:13.500 --> 00:31:19.339
Shiny application that, you know, a user comes in, and they want to run the model. And so this

00:31:19.339 --> 00:31:23.420
takes about a minute. And the user knows that they know it's going to take some time. So they click

00:31:23.420 --> 00:31:27.660
run model, they go grab some coffee. And when they come back, the models trained and ready to be

00:31:27.660 --> 00:31:33.819
interacted with. But here we can get into an issue where let's say you have a user come in,

00:31:33.819 --> 00:31:38.459
and they want to run a model. So they click model. And then right afterwards, you want to have these

00:31:38.459 --> 00:31:43.819
users come in and plot some data. But now they essentially have to wait for this model to

00:31:43.819 --> 00:31:49.099
complete before they can plot the data. So something that used to take less than a second

00:31:49.099 --> 00:31:53.900
can now take, you know, over 60 seconds. And this is going to result in these users being very

00:31:53.900 --> 00:32:00.140
confused of why is it going so slow, and they're not going to be happy. So instead, we can implement

00:32:00.140 --> 00:32:05.020
something known as promises in this async programming. And we essentially make our slow

00:32:05.020 --> 00:32:10.859
running steps a promise. So we tell this user that wants to run a model that, hey, your model,

00:32:10.859 --> 00:32:15.660
it's going to take some time, and it will eventually complete, I promise you, it will complete.

00:32:16.540 --> 00:32:22.859
But what this allows you to do is to also serve those fast running steps instantaneously.

00:32:22.859 --> 00:32:29.020
So user comes in, they run the model. And if these users log in, essentially, the model pauses,

00:32:29.020 --> 00:32:33.979
it serves these users, because the steps are very fast, one second, and once they're done,

00:32:33.979 --> 00:32:36.300
it can come back to the model and finish that step.

00:32:38.859 --> 00:32:43.500
All right, so we talked about a bunch of different ways to how to improve your Shiny application and

00:32:43.500 --> 00:32:49.500
make them slightly more production ready. Let's just review some of those steps. And here I'm

00:32:49.500 --> 00:32:53.819
just going to use this example Shiny application where we have the UI here in these red steps,

00:32:53.819 --> 00:32:57.739
server in the yellow, and then we have some attached data to the Shiny application.

00:32:58.699 --> 00:33:03.819
The first thing we talked about was preparing your data in advance. You can see right here in

00:33:03.819 --> 00:33:08.459
our server function, we have a step to clean the data. Well, if you don't need to have this in your

00:33:08.459 --> 00:33:13.739
Shiny application, you can certainly remove it, put it inside of an R Markdown or a Corrido document,

00:33:13.739 --> 00:33:19.900
scheduled to run elsewhere, have it in a pin. And then also, again, anywhere and anytime you can

00:33:19.900 --> 00:33:25.180
have your Shiny application not necessarily be bundled with the data itself and have that data

00:33:25.819 --> 00:33:31.579
stored elsewhere, either in a database or a pin or a plumber API, that is certainly going to be our

00:33:31.579 --> 00:33:38.780
best practice. Next, we talked about how to optimize and organize your code and your functions.

00:33:39.660 --> 00:33:45.099
So one thing we, in this silly application, we're using this read.csv function, which is

00:33:45.099 --> 00:33:50.219
a great function for reading in CSV files, but it's not necessarily the fastest one. And there's

00:33:50.219 --> 00:33:55.260
other functions out there that can be used, including this fread function. And then we can

00:33:55.260 --> 00:34:00.619
also think about taking some of these steps and moving it outside of any reactive functions. So

00:34:00.619 --> 00:34:04.780
again, you're not rereading in the same data step over and over and over again.

00:34:07.020 --> 00:34:10.139
Then we talked about caching your output. So that pizzeria example.

00:34:11.100 --> 00:34:16.780
So if you have any outputs of your Shiny application, like the render outputs,

00:34:16.780 --> 00:34:20.860
and those outputs kind of are dependent on a certain combination of inputs,

00:34:20.860 --> 00:34:26.459
it can essentially generate those. It can see those inputs, generate the output, and then

00:34:26.459 --> 00:34:31.500
store that output. So if it ever sees that combination of inputs ever again,

00:34:31.500 --> 00:34:36.060
then it can simply retrieve it from the cache rather than having to compute it all over again.

00:34:37.820 --> 00:34:42.379
And then finally, we talked about async programming. For our Shiny application here,

00:34:42.379 --> 00:34:46.780
we have two steps. It creates a model. It also renders the plot. But the modeling step,

00:34:46.780 --> 00:34:51.899
this takes a long time. With the rendering a plot, that goes really fast. So essentially,

00:34:51.899 --> 00:34:57.820
what we can do is we can promise the user that the slow running steps will eventually finish,

00:34:57.820 --> 00:35:00.379
but it will allow the fast jobs to complete first.

00:35:03.340 --> 00:35:08.780
All right, so those are just a few of the steps for creating more production-ready Shiny

00:35:08.780 --> 00:35:13.820
applications. It's certainly not an exhaustive list. And again, that Mastering Shiny book I

00:35:13.820 --> 00:35:17.979
mentioned before, it will also be a great resource for creating more production-ready Shiny apps.

